2026-07-22 10:00:00", "open": 17.40713, "high": 17.40888, "low": 17.39932, "close": 17.40022}, {"time": "2026-07-22 11:00:00", "open": 17.40184, "high": 17.40538, "low": 17.39541, "close": 17.39775}, {"time": "2026-07-22 12:00:00", "open": 17.39774, "high": 17.40671, "low": 17.39408, "close": 17.39603}, {"time": "2026-07-22 13:00:00", "open": 17.39564, "high": 17.40216, "low": 17.39271, "close": 17.39917}, {"time": "2026-07-22 14:00:00", "open": 17.39879, "high": 17.39879, "low": 17.39727, "close": 17.39733}], "calendar": [], "editorial": "The peso has quietly asserted itself over recent sessions, with USD/MXN drifting to current levels around 17.397 after failing to sustain a push above the 17.60 area seen in late June. The daily chart tells a story of a pair that reached a near-term ceiling and has since been grinding lower in a measured, relatively orderly fashion \u2014 not a collapse, but a steady erosion of dollar strength against the Mexican currency.\n\nThe structure story is one of compression within a well-defined corridor. The pair put in its recent swing high around 17.667 on 24 June, and from that point the daily candles have traced a sequence of lower highs. The prior reaction zone at 17.508 has proven particularly significant \u2014 it has attracted three distinct reactions and now sits as a meaningful overhead reference. Below that, the 17.432 zone carries even more weight, having registered six touches across the lookback window; price has repeatedly stalled or reversed in that vicinity, and the current print is now trading beneath it. That shift in positioning \u2014 from price oscillating around 17.43 to now sitting below it \u2014 is worth noting. To the downside, the 17.350 area represents the next structural reference, a prior reaction zone with three touches, and below that the 17.257 zone offers a more substantial support cluster built over five prior reactions.\n\nThe intraday picture on the H1 chart is one of remarkable compression. Over the past 24 hours, the pair has barely moved, oscillating in a roughly 50-pip band between approximately 17.375 and 17.423. There was a brief push to 17.422 during the European morning session, but that was promptly faded, and price has since settled back into the lower portion of the range. The H1 candles are small-bodied and overlapping \u2014 a classic consolidation signature that offers little directional conviction in isolation. The market appears to be in a holding pattern.\n\nThe economic calendar carries no scheduled events of note for today, which means the pair is unlikely to receive any fundamental catalyst to break it out of this tight range in the near term. Absent a data surprise or an unexpected headline from either Washington or Mexico City, the current drift is likely to persist through the session.\n\nIn terms of what would alter the read: a reclaim and daily close above the 17.432 prior reaction zone would neutralise the modest bearish drift and bring the 17.508 resistance back into focus. Conversely, a clean break and close beneath the 17.350 support zone would represent a meaningful structural deterioration for the dollar side of the pair and open the path toward the deeper 17.257 cluster. Until either of those scenarios materialises, the desk's neutral framing reflects a pair caught between two well-established structural boundaries with no immediate catalyst to resolve the tension.\n\nThis is editorial analysis, not financial advice. Trading involves substantial risk of loss.", "sample": false}